org.iotivity.service.client

Class RcsRemoteResourceObject

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.iotivity.service.RcsObject
      • org.iotivity.service.client.RcsRemoteResourceObject

  • public final class RcsRemoteResourceObject
extends RcsObject
    This represents a remote resource and provides simple ways to interact with it. Basically this is a client of a remote resource that runs on other device. The class supports features to help get information of a remote resource such as monitoring and caching.
    See Also:
    RcsDiscoveryManager

      • startMonitoring

        public void startMonitoring(RcsRemoteResourceObject.OnStateChangedListener listener)
                     throws RcsException
        Starts monitoring the resource.

        Monitoring provides a feature to check the presence of a resource, even when the server is not announcing Presence using startPresnece.

        Parameters:
        listener - the listener to receive new state.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if listener is null
        RcsIllegalStateException - if monitoring is already started
        RcsDestroyedObjectException - if the object is already destroyed
        RcsException
        See Also:
        RcsRemoteResourceObject.ResourceState, isMonitoring(), stopMonitoring()

      • startCaching

        public void startCaching()
                  throws RcsException
        Starts caching attributes of the resource. This will start data caching for the resource. Once caching started it will look for the data updation on the resource and updates the cache data accordingly.

        It is equivalent to calling startCaching(OnCacheUpdatedListener) with null.

        Throws:
        RcsDestroyedObjectException - if the object is already destroyed
        RcsException
        See Also:
        startCaching(OnCacheUpdatedListener), isCaching(), getCacheState(), getCachedAttribute(String), getCachedAttributes(), RcsRemoteResourceObject.OnCacheUpdatedListener
